drew a random number R uniformly distributed in [0, 1) that is used to get s in the following way:
s = 0 if R > e−4k s = 1 if e−4k > R > e−8k s = 2 if e−8k > R > e−12k s = 3 if e−12k > R
In Ito and Kanada’s original proposal, the 32 bits in a memory word represent spins in different samples [i.e., 32 different realizations of the couplings Jx,y in Eq. (1); this is why this simpler version of the algorithm is some times named multi-sample multi-spin coding]. The algorithm includes also two 32-bits daemon words id0 and id1. The j-th bit in id0 provides the least significant bit of a two-bit integer s[j] (of course, the most significant bit of s[j] is the j-th bit in id1). In a multi-sample setting [11], it was a perfectly reasonable choice to draw just two daemon bits d0 and d1 as explained above, and then set the 32 bits in id0 identical to d0 (id1 is formed in an analogous way from the single bit d1).
However, our MCQSG program leverages multispin coding by packing 32 spins from the same system in a 32-bit memory word. In other words, ours is a multi-site multi-spin coding method. Hence, it is mandatory (for us) to code 32 statistically independent integers s[j] in our daemon words id0 and id1. A simple solution is just drawing 32 independent random numbers R, so that an independent integer s is obtained from each R but we found out a more efficient approach.
Our solution requires obtaining three statistically independent random words b4, b8 and b12. Our requirements for the 32 bits in these memory words are:
• all bits should be statistically independent;
• (each bit) equal to zero with probability equal to 1 − e−4k
The procedure we follow to obtain the daemon words id1 and id2 from b4, b8 and b12 is explained in B. Thus, our problem boils down to obtaining three 32-bit words b4, b8 and b12 with the prescribed statistical properties. We obtain these words through the following procedure. To obtain the 32 bits in (say) b4, we use four “50/50” 64 bits random words (i.e, each bit has the same probability of being either equal to 0 or equal to 1) obtained from our own CUDA implementation of D.E. Shaws’s counter-based philox 4x32 10 parallel generator [13].2 We combine the 128 bits from philox 4x32 10 with another set of 128 bits produced by a single iteration of the xoroshiro128++ transformation [14].3 Then, 8 bit random integers are generated as follows:
