2. A trick to speedup the CUDA implementation
In our program coverlap pt, we decided that a single thread would take care of all the operations corresponding to a pair of Euclidean times (τ1, τ2) and a pair of Monte Carlo times (t1, t2), recall Eq. (E2). The 1024 threads in a block share the assignment of Monte Carlo times (t1, t2) and build the pairs (τ1, τ2) by exhausting all the possible combinations of a list of 32 possible values of τ1 with another list of 32 values for τ2. In other words, given a replica index a, it suffices to bring to the GPU shared memory just 64 planes of spins Sx,τ (t, a): 32 planes with fixed t = t1 and τ = τ1, the other 32 planes with fixed t = t2 and τ = τ2. The information contained in these 64 planes is enough for the 1024 threads to carry out all their intended operations. A simple variation of the same idea works for corr euclidea and overlap tau.

